7.1     [High] Certain combinations of instructions can lead to token loss
     File(s): RouterGateway.cairo
     Description: Through the RouterGateway contract, users can choose to execute multiple sequential instructions on a single gateway.
     Before executing the instructions, the contract checks its token balances. After execution, it calculates the balance changes and transfers
     tokens to the user accordingly. However, since the pre-execution balance includes tokens that are meant to be input (e.g., for deposit or
     repay), certain combinations of instructions may result in token loss.

1    fn before_send_instructions(...) -> Span<u256> {
2        let mut i: usize = 0;
3        let mut balancesBefore = array![];
4        while i != instructions.len() {
5            match instructions.at(i) {
6                LendingInstruction::Deposit(deposit) => {
7                    let basic = *deposit.basic;
8                    let erc20 = IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: basic.token };
9                    if should_transfer {
10                       assert(erc20.transfer_from(get_caller_address(), get_contract_address(), basic.amount), 'transfer
                          ↪  failed');
11                   }
12                   assert(erc20.approve(gateway, basic.amount), 'approve failed');
13                   let balance = erc20.balance_of(get_contract_address());
14                   balancesBefore.append(balance);
15               },
16               LendingInstruction::Repay(repay) => {
17                   let basic = *repay.basic;
18                   let erc20 = IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: basic.token };
19                   if should_transfer {
20                       assert(erc20.transfer_from(get_caller_address(), get_contract_address(), basic.amount), 'transfer
                          ↪  failed');
21                   }
22                   assert(erc20.approve(gateway, basic.amount), 'approve failed');
23                   let balance = erc20.balance_of(get_contract_address());
24                   balancesBefore.append(balance);
25               },
26               //...

     Some combinations of instructions may lead to token loss. For example:

         1. repay token1 with 100;
         2. withdraw to retrieve 110 of token1;

     Since 100 token1 tokens are input into the contract in advance, balanceBefore = [100, 100] During execution, 100 token1 tokens are
     used to repay the debt, and the withdraw retrieves 110 tokens. balanceAfter = 110 - 100 = 10 Only 10 token1 tokens are sent to the
     user, while the remaining 100 tokens remain locked in the contract.
     Impact: Certain instructions combinations that use the same token can lead to permanent loss.
     Recommendation(s): It is recommended that after_send_instructions fetch the token balances before any token inputs occur, and then
     iterate through the instructions to execute token inputs.
     Status: Fixed
