7.6     [Low] Nostra positions are not getting tracked correctly
     File(s): NostraGateway.cairo
     Description: In the Nostra protocol there are 2 types of collateral that users can have, Interest Bearing collateral and Non-Interest Bearing
     collateral. It is possible that users hold both of these debt tokens simultaneously. However, the get_user_positions(...) function doesn’t
     account for this scenario:

1    fn get_user_positions(
 2       self: @ContractState, user: ContractAddress,
 3   ) -> Array<(ContractAddress, felt252, u256, u256)> {
 4       let mut positions = array![];
 5       let mut i = 0;
 6       while i != self.supported_assets.len() {
 7           let underlying = self.supported_assets.at(i).read();
 8           let symbol = IERC20SymbolDispatcher { contract_address: underlying }.symbol();
 9
10             let debt = self.underlying_to_ndebt.read(underlying);
11             let collateral = self.underlying_to_ncollateral.read(underlying);
12             let ibcollateral = self.underlying_to_nibcollateral.read(underlying);
13
14             let debt_balance = IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: debt }.balance_of(user);
15             let collateral_raw = IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: collateral }
16                 .balance_of(user);
17
18             // @audit User can have collateral in both the collateral and ibcollateral tokens
19             let collateral_balance = if collateral_raw == 0 {
20                 IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: ibcollateral }.balance_of(user)
21             } else {
22                 collateral_raw
23             };
24             positions.append((underlying, symbol, debt_balance, collateral_balance));
25             i += 1;
26         };
27         return positions;
28   }

     The function checks the user’s Non-Interest Bearing collateral balance and only if it’s 0 it checks for user’s Interest Bearing collateral
     balance.
     Impact: The function always returns the balance of 1 type of collateral that the user holds and never the total of both of them. If a user is
     holding Non-Interest Bearing collateral tokens, his Interest Bearing collateral balance will not be accounted for.
     Recommendation(s): Check for both of the balances and add them.
     Status: Acknowledged
     Update from Kapan: This one won’t be fixed in the release version as the UI does not support the nostra semantics. Users would be
     required to go through their portal to setup the tokens correctly for transfering debt for the time being.

                                                                                                                                              11
     CODESPECT

7.7     [Low] The on_flash_loan(...) function does not take the repay_all flag into ac-
             count when handling the repay instruction
     File(s): RouterGateway.cairo
     Description: In the on_flash_loan function, funds are obtained via flash loan to prepare for debt repayment. The total repay amount is
     recalculated and the repay instruction is reconstructed. However, since the repay_all flag is not taken into account, some of these checks
     may become invalid.

1    fn on_flash_loan(...) {
 2       //...
 3       for protocolInstruction in protocol_instructions {
 4           for instruction in protocolInstruction.instructions {
 5               if let LendingInstruction::Repay(repay) = instruction {
 6                   let repay = *repay;
 7                   repay_amounts.append(repay.basic.amount);
 8                   total_repay_amount += repay.basic.amount;
 9                   repay_count += 1;
10               }
11           }
12       }
13
14         // Calculate remaining amount to distribute
15         let remaining_amount = amount - total_repay_amount;
16         assert(remaining_amount >= 0, 'flashloan insufficient');
17         //...
18         for instruction in protocol_instructions {
19                //...
20                             basic: BasicInstruction {
21                                 token: repay.basic.token,
22                                 amount: modified_amount,
23                                 user: repay.basic.user,
24                             },
25                             repay_all: false, // Force explicit amount
26                             context: repay.context,
27
28            //...

     When determining the flash loan amount, if the repay_all flag is enabled in the repay instruction, the flash loan amount is treated as the
     full debt rather than repay.amount.
     However, in the on_flash_loan function, during validation and instruction reconstruction, repay.amount is used without handling the
     repay_all flag explicitly. This may lead to invalid or ineffective checks.
     Impact: If repay_all is enabled and repay.amount does not match the full debt amount, then the move_debt function may fail.
     Recommendation(s): The on_flash_loan function should consider the repay_all flag when accumulating amounts and reconstructing
     repay instructions.
     Status: Fixed
     Update from Kapan:

                                                                                                                                           12
     CODESPECT

7.8     [Low] get_flash_loan_amount(...) may fail to return the correct amount
     File(s): RouterGateway.cairo
     Description: In the get_flash_loan_amount(...) function, if a repay instruction has the repay_all flag enabled, the function will immedi-
     ately return the flash loan amount for the gateway. However, the function does not consider whether the other ProtocolInstructions also
     contains a repay instruction.

1    fn get_flash_loan_amount(...) {
2       let mut flash_loan_amount : u256 = 0;
 3      let mut token : ContractAddress = Zero::zero();
 4      for protocolInstruction in instructions {
 5           for instruction in protocolInstruction.instructions {
 6               if let LendingInstruction::Repay(repay) = instruction {
 7                   assert(*repay.basic.amount != 0, 'repay-amount-is-zero');
 8                   if *repay.repay_all {
 9                       let gateway = ILendingInstructionProcessorDispatcher { contract_address:
                          ↪  self.gateways.read(*protocolInstruction.protocol_name) };
10                       return (*repay.basic.token, gateway.get_flash_loan_amount(*repay));
11                   }
12                   flash_loan_amount += *repay.basic.amount;
13                   token = *repay.basic.token;
14               }
15           };
16      };
17      //...
18   }

     Impact: If there are multiple ProtocolInstructions in the array and one of the repay instructions has the repay_all flag enabled, due to
     the absence of the required amount in other repay instructions, the flash loan amount will be insufficient, causing the move_debt instruction
     to fail.
     Recommendation(s): When the repay_all flag is enabled, do not consider the flash loan amount required for just a single market.
     Status: Fixed
     Update from Kapan:

                                                                                                                                              13
     CODESPECT

7.9     [Best Practice] Revoke excess approvals in after_send_instructions(...)
     File(s): RouterGateway.cairo
     Description: In after_send_instructions, there may be cases where not all tokens are used during repayment because repay.amount >
     debt. The unused tokens will be transferred from the router to the user. However, the approval for these tokens granted to the gateway in
     before_send_instructions has not yet been revoked.

1    fn after_send_instructions(ref self: ContractState, gateway: ContractAddress, instructions: Span<LendingInstruction>,
      ↪  balancesBefore: Span<u256>, should_transfer: bool) -> Span<u256> {
2    // ...
3            LendingInstruction::Repay(repay) => {
4                let basic = *repay.basic;
5                let erc20 = IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: basic.token };
6                let balance = erc20.balance_of(get_contract_address());
7                let diff = *balancesBefore.at(i) - balance;
8                balancesAfter.append(diff);
9                if basic.amount > diff {
10                   let erc20 = IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: basic.token };
11                   erc20.transfer(basic.user, basic.amount - diff);
12               }
13           },
14   // ...
15   }

     Impact: A user can manipulate the system to cause the router to grant an excessively large approval to the gateway. For example, if user1
     only has a debt of 10 but sets repay.amount to 10,000 during repayment, the unused 9,990 tokens will be returned to user1. However, the
     router’s approval of 9,990 tokens to the gateway remains in place.
     While this may not have an immediate visible impact, it is recommended to revoke this unused approval to reduce the potential attack
     surface in future updates.
     Recommendation(s): It is recommended to revoke the router’s approval to the gateway for the refunded tokens.
     Status: Fixed
